04781nam a2200613Ia 9780520335783DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20231990cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203357837 a10.1525/97805203357832doi  a(DE-B1597)569422  a(OCoLC)1198931466  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDD801.P448 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a943/.4350041 aApplegate, Celia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Nation of Provincials :bThe German Idea of Heimat /cCelia Applegate.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (286 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tONE. Heimat and German Identity -- tTWO. Taming the Revolution -- tTHREE. The Heimat Movement -- tFOUR. The Great War on the Home Front -- tFIVE. Saving the Heimat -- tSIX. A Republic of Hometownsmen -- tSEVEN. From Homeland to Borderland -- tEIGHT. Heimat and the Recovery of Identity -- tBibliography -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the center of this pioneering work in modern European history is the German word Heimat—the homeland, the local place. Translations barely penetrate the meaning of the word, which has provided the emotional and ideological common ground for a variety of associations and individuals devoted to the cause of local preservation. Celia Applegate examines at both the national and regional levels the cultural meaning of Heimat and why it may be pivotal to the troubled and very timely question of German identity. The ideas and activities clustered around Heimat shed new light particularly on problems of modernization. Instead of viewing the Germans as a dangerously anti-modern people, Applegate argues that they used the cultivation of Heimat to ground an abstract nationalism in their attachment to familiar places and to reconcile the modern industrial and urban world with the rural landscapes and customs they admired. Primarily a characteristic of the middle classes, love of Heimat constituted an alternative vision of German unity to the familiar aggressive, militaristic one. The Heimat vision of Germany emphasized cultural diversity and defined German identity by its internal members rather than its external enemies. Applegate asks that we re-examine the continuities of German history from the perspective of the local places that made up Germany, rather than from that of prominent intellectuals or national policymakers. The local patriotism of Heimat activists emerges as an element of German culture that persisted across the great divides of 1918, 1933, and 1945. She also suggests that this attachment to a particular place is a feature of Europeans in general and is deserving of further attention. This title is part of UC Press's Voices Revived program, which commemorates University of California Press’s mission to seek out and cultivate the brightest minds and give them voice, reach, and impact. Drawing on a backlist dating to 1893, Voices Revived makes high-quality, peer-reviewed scholarship accessible once again using print-on-demand technology. This title was originally published in 1990.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEthnicityzGermanyzPalatinate. 0aEthnologyzGermanyzPalatinate. 4aGerman history. 4aGermany. 4acultural and social ethnology. 4aethnology. 4ahistory. 4aidentity. 4anationalism. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520335783?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520335783423Coveruhttps://www